# Probability and Axioms

Probability measures the likelihood of an event occurring.

## Sample Space (S)

The set of all possible outcomes of an experiment.

Example:

```text
Tossing a coin

S = {Heads, Tails}
```

---

## Event

A subset of the sample space.

Example:

```text
Event A = Getting Heads
```

---

## Probability

The likelihood of an event occurring.

Formula:

[
P(A)=\frac{\text{Number of Favorable Outcomes}}
{\text{Total Number of Outcomes}}
]

Example:

```text
P(Heads) = 1/2 = 0.5
```

---

## Probability Axioms

### Axiom 1: Non-Negativity

[
P(A) \ge 0
]

Probability can never be negative.

---

### Axiom 2: Normalization

[
P(S)=1
]

The probability of the entire sample space is always 1.

---

### Axiom 3: Additivity

For mutually exclusive events:

[
P(A \cup B)=P(A)+P(B)
]

---

# Bayes' Theorem

Bayes' Theorem helps update probabilities when new evidence becomes available.

Formula:

[
P(A|B)=
\frac{P(B|A)\times P(A)}
{P(B)}
]

---

## Components of Bayes' Theorem

### Posterior

[
P(A|B)
]

Updated probability after observing evidence.

---

### Likelihood

[
P(B|A)
]

Probability of observing evidence given the event.

---

### Prior

[
P(A)
]

Initial belief before observing evidence.

---

### Evidence

[
P(B)
]

Overall probability of observing the evidence.

---

## Applications

* Medical Diagnosis
* Spam Detection
* Fraud Detection
* Machine Learning

